The Herald Zvamaida Murwira Senior Reporter President Mnangagwa has today held a ground breaking ceremony for the construction of the Museum of Africa Liberation in Harare aimed at documenting the liberation struggle of the continent. <img class="size-full wp-image-518550" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3098-copy.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3098-copy.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3098-copy-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> President Mnangagwa receives the late National Hero Cde Josiah Magama Tongogara’s pistol from his widow Angeline and son Tichafa (holding a microphone) at the ground breaking ceremony of the Museum of African Liberation in Warren Park, Harare today. In his keynote address, President Mnangagwa said the glamorous institution will enable the African continent to tell its history. <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-518555" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3452-copy.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3452-copy.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3452-copy-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> In today’s event, liberation artefacts for several liberation icons were presented to President Mnangagwa for them to be kept in the Museum as souvenirs. <img class="size-full wp-image-518558" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3416.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3416.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3416-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> President Mnangagwa addresses members of Zanu-PF after he officiated at the ground breaking ceremony of the Museum of African Liberation in Warren Park, Harare today. They include artefacts for former Vice Presidents Simon Muzenda, Joseph Msika, liberation icons Cdes Josiah Tongogara, Leopold Takawira among others. <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-518561" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3330-copy.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3330-copy.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3330-copy-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Artefacts for other liberation icons from the African continent who include Kwame Nkrumah are expected to be deposited with the museum soon. <img class="size-full wp-image-518560" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3256-1.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3256-1.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/12/849A3256-1-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> President Mnangagwa prepares a basin to plant a tree at the ground breaking ceremony of the Museum of African Liberation in Warren Park, Harare today.  President Mnangagwa later planted a tree at the site with several ambassadors accredited to Zimbabwe doing the same.